description:
lichen_util.h:31-38 implements secure_zero with a byte-by-byte volatile write loop. On most embedded platforms, this is fine for small buffers (16-32 bytes). However, the link_ctx cleanup (project-LICHEN-rwio.1) calls secure_zero on the entire link_ctx struct which may be 100+ bytes.

What goes wrong: On larger structures, byte-by-byte writes are measurably slower than word-aligned volatile writes. In a disable path (lichen_l2_enable with state=false), this adds latency while holding both tx_mutex and rx_mutex.

Consider:
```c
static inline void secure_zero(void *ptr, size_t len)
{
    volatile uint8_t *p = ptr;
    /* Word-aligned bulk zeroing for larger buffers */
    while (len >= sizeof(unsigned long) && 
           ((uintptr_t)p & (sizeof(unsigned long) - 1)) == 0) {
        *(volatile unsigned long *)p = 0;
        p += sizeof(unsigned long);
        len -= sizeof(unsigned long);
    }
    /* Byte cleanup for remainder */
    while (len--) {
        *p++ = 0;
    }
    compiler_barrier();
}
```

This is only worth doing if profiling shows disable latency is a problem. Current implementation is correct, just potentially slower.
